ownedComment.body: A simple scale for binary values (with no additional constraints to support additional semantics for true and false values)
A scale for binary values (with additional constraints to provide additional semantics for true and false values corresponding to specifed BinaryValue terms)
A scale that holds decimal numeric values.
A scale that contains values that are themselves members of a hierarchical data structure (an 'is-a' hierarchy, a partonomy, etc). The scale is specified by denoting the 'top' value in the hierarchy.
A scale that holds integer numeric values.

An abstract class (that cannot itself be instantiated) that denotes the mathematical properties of values associated with specific variables. The measurement scale denotes the data properties of the measurement but does not itself denote the quality that the variable is measuring. Each scale provides characteristics of a set of values that associated with variables.
A scale whose elements consist of a set of items. The items are assumed to be mutually exclusive.
This scale describes the situation when you have a set of strings as the sets of objects in question. Accepts any strings or terms.
The abstract class for measurement scales that accept scalar, numeric values.
If this is a circular scale. A circular scale will wrap around from the maximum to the minimum value. One example would be degrees of rotation, which goes from 0 (inclusive) to 360 (exclusive).
If the minimum value specified by the scale includes the endpoint. - ignore this if 'hasMinimum' is false
If the maximum value specified by the scale includes the endpoint. - ignore this if 'hasMaximum' is false
The scale has a set minimum value.
The scale has a set maximum value.
A scale whose elements consist of ranked, ordered values.

If this is true, then data where the ranked values are equal may be considered equal. Otherwise not. For example, if two labeling patterns are both scored 'moderately dense' they could *not* really be considered equally dense.
Assume values are integer ranks

This scale permits the definition of anonymous measurement value terms of a specified type based only on relations to a named set of measurement values. Thus, an example would be an anonymous brain region defined by virtue of it topological relationships with other brain regions (this is essential for the definition of injection sites in neuroanatomical experiments).
A nominal scale that determines the values that can be used as the range of the relations.

Note that this value is notionally a Set and should not contain duplicates and it is not semantically ordered. It is represented as a list so that the order of values is maintained for user-interface purposes.

@return the relativeTermType
@return the allowedRelations
@return the valueScale
@return the allowedValues from the values Scale
@param scale the valueScale to set
@param relativeTermType the relativeTermType to set
@param allowedRelations the allowedRelations to set
A nominal scale whose value elements are all drawn from a fully enumerated set of NominalValue terms.
@return the allowedValues
@param allowedValues the allowedValues to set
An ordinal scale whose elements consist of ranked, ordered values that are all drawn from a predefined set of OrdinalValue terms.

Note that this value is an ordered Set and should not contain duplicates.
TODO: Make this be an immutable collection.
An ordinal scale whose elements consist of ranked, ordered values with a specified maximum rank.
A scale that holds numeric values that denote a specific isntant in time.
A scale that denotes a passage of natural language text.
A scale for composite values containing parts are made up of variables.
A set of entities, processes, and variables that may be specified as relevant to the construction of models within a scientific experimental domain.

The symbolic representation of a quantity that is either set or measured within a scientific experiment. An ExperimentalVariable assumes a specific, well-defined value of a given type and measures some quality of an entity that may be specified as a term from an external ontology.
A value for a binary scale that can either denote 'true' or 'false' within a given context.
A value for a numeric scale that denotes a single measurement of an integer.
An abstract class denoting a value derived from a specific measurement of a specific variable.
A value for a numeric scale that denotes a single measurement of a decimal number.
A value for a nominal scale. This value can only be compared to other values and evaluated as being either 'equal to' or 'not equal to' other values.
A scalar value for a numeric scale. This value can be treated as a number in mathematical operation.

A value for a ordinal scale. This value can only be compared to other values and evaluated as being either 'greater than' or 'less than' other values. If the OrdinalScale associated with this value has its 'equalsAreEqual' property set to true, then this value may also support an equality operation with other values.
A value for a relative scale.
A measurement value that is drawn from a specified hierarchical scale where the hierarchical structure is defined by the presence of a defined relation.
An entity that is involved in a scientific experiment.
A process that is involved in a scientific experiment.
A physical object (equivalent to obo:BFO_0000040) that may participate in an experimental process.
An entity that is made up of information (equivalent to obo:IAO_0000030) that may participate in an experimental process.
An assay is an OoevvProcess that takes a MaterialEntity as input and generates an Information entity as output .
An OoevvProcess that takes a MaterialEntity as input and generates an MaterialEntity as output.
A DataTransformation is an OoevvProcess that takes a InformationEntity as input and generates an InformationEntity as output .
Any procedural step within an experimental design (equivalent to obo:OBI_0000011).
